<span id="vi.iv.xix.i-p2"></span><span class="c1"><span
id="vi.iv.xix.i-p2.1"></span>Chapter I.—Simon Wishes to Discuss with
Peter the Unity of God.</span>

<span id="vi.iv.xix.i-p3"></span><span class="c9"><span
id="vi.iv.xix.i-p3.1"></span>At</span> break of day Peter went out, and
reaching the place where he was wont to discourse, he saw a great
multitude assembled.  At the very time when he was going to discourse,
one of his deacons entered, and said:  “Simon has come from
Antioch, <span id="fr_1246"></span>[1247](#fn_1246.md) starting as soon as
it was evening, having learned that you promised to speak on the
unity <span id="fr_1247"></span>[1248](#fn_1247.md) of God; and he is
ready, along with Athenodorus the Epicurean, to come to hear your
speech, in order that he may publicly oppose all the arguments ever
adduced by you for the unity of God.”  Just as the deacon said this, lo!
Simon himself entered, accompanied by Athenodorus and some other
friends.  And before Peter spoke at all, he took the first word, and
said:—

