<span id="vi.iv.xix.i-p4"></span> \[Homilies XVI.–XIX., giving the
details of a second discussion with Simon at Laodicea, are peculiar to
this narrative.  Much of the matter finds a parallel in the longer
account of the previous discussion at Cæsarea in *Recognitions*, ii.
iii. (comp. Homily III.), but all the circumstances are different. 
Uhlhorn formerly regarded this portion of the *Homilies* as the nucleus
of the entire literature.  He has modified his view.  An analysis of the
discussion cannot be attempted; but in the footnote to *Recognitions*,
ii. 19, a general comparison is given of the three accounts of
discussions with Simon Magus.—R.\]

<span id="fn_1247"></span>[312:1248](0081053.htm#fr_1247.md) <span
id="vi.iv.xix.i-p4.1"></span>

<span id="vi.iv.xix.i-p5"></span> The word properly signifies the “sole
government or monarchy of God.”  It means that God alone is ruler.

